b'I would also argue that it is best keep the number risky players you own to a minimum due to the limited number of FTs we are allowed\n\nMost importantly, be honest with yourself. Only Pep/TT know if Foden and Chilwell are nailed. We FPL managers are all reading the line\xe2\x80\xa6'

b'The manager might also realise that Foden is likely to score with higher variance than a similar nailed player e.g.: Foden, Zaha & Tielemans all scored ~130 points last season but with variance of 19.3, 18.7 and 8.7 respectively w Foden topping the notoriously inconsistent Zaha\xe2\x80\xa6'

b"@wiserthanyoda @ShaunWebber @JRGN7 @danmote1 @kop6_ @_pauljoyce I'll never see why people thought Foden had a great game. Milner was just that bad that Downing could have been on that wing and he'd have been useless"

b'I am saying that I do believe navigating such players is a harder way to play the game. I will end with this;\n\nA clear minded manager might analyse that although Foden only played ~50% of league mins last season, he is in line to get closer to 75% of mins based on other factors\xe2\x80\xa6'

b'I am not advocating that we boycott players that are not nailed (nor am I picking on Foden as this applies to others e.g. Chilwell)\n\nIn fact I believe navigating such players might hold the key to cracking the game which is what upside chasers like @lateriser12 are trying to do\xe2\x80\xa6'

b'I might argue that in our imaginary scenario, the FPL manager should keep Foden as he would be in form and have started the expected % of mins. But that would require great emotional control, which is the second part of my argument.\n\nOwning risky players is emotionally draining\xe2\x80\xa6'

b'With nailed players, most of us simply monitor the player\xe2\x80\x99s form, fixtures and stats. If the nailed player doesn\xe2\x80\x99t start, then we consider that as well because that is new information.\n\nIn our imaginary scenario, Foden would likely have played over 70% of all mins as expected\xe2\x80\xa6'

b'Firstly, it can be incredibly difficult to decide when to sell such a player, especially when the dice doesn\xe2\x80\x99t roll your way\n\nImagine WCing in Foden and he comes off the bench for a 1 pointer in GW8, then starts & scores in the UCL and then comes on for another 1 pointer in GW9\xe2\x80\xa6'

b'I guess Torres\xe2\x80\x99 injury makes Foden and Mahrez slightly more tempting. But I would still likely swerve them, even on a wildcard\n\nI believe owning risky (not nailed) players is hard! These players can hinder the ability of an FPL manager to properly manage his team\xe2\x80\xa6'
